This paper deals with caching and device-to-device (D2D) communications in mobile networks, which are primarily studied in the computer science subfield of networking and internet architecture (cs.NI). The paper also involves modeling and analyzing the performance of the network, which falls under the subfield of information theory (cs.IT). Additionally, the paper considers the impact of user mobility on the network performance, which is a topic of interest in the subfield of distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC). The use of caching and D2D communications also has implications for social and information networks (cs.SI). Finally, the paper involves simulations to validate the analytical results, which is a common approach in multimedia (cs.MM) research.
